THOUGHT

The source is extremely small: a 256-byte global buffer at `program.c:8`, and `main` blindly copies the first command-line argument into it using `strcpy` at `program.c:11`. The ASan report confirms a global-buffer-overflow in `strcpy`; the long repro argument is 600 bytes plus the terminating NUL, so `strcpy` attempts a 601-byte write into a 256-byte object. Boundary testing also showed that an input of length 255 succeeds, while length 256 fails because the NUL terminator requires a 257th byte.

ROOT CAUSE: `program.c:11` calls `strcpy(buf, argc[1])` where `buf` is `char buf[256]` from `program.c:8`. `strcpy` has no knowledge of the destination size and copies until it reaches the source NUL terminator. Any argument longer than 255 characters overflows the global buffer, corrupting the global redzone/adjacent memory and triggering the sanitizer. There is also no `argc` count validation despite confusing parameter names (`int argv, char **argc`), so missing arguments would be a separate out-of-bounds/null use risk.

LOCAL FIX: Validate the argument count and bound the copy to the actual destination size while ensuring NUL termination. Minimal replacement:
```diff
+ #include <stdio.h>
+ #include <stdlib.h>
+ #include <string.h>
+
  char buf[256];

- int main(int argv,char **argc) {
-     strcpy(buf,argc[1]);
+ int main(int argc, char **argv) {
+     if (argc < 2) {
+         fprintf(stderr, "usage: %s <string>\n", argv[0]);
+         return 2;
+     }
+     if (strlen(argv[1]) >= sizeof buf) {
+         fprintf(stderr, "input too long: max %zu bytes\n", sizeof buf - 1);
+         return 1;
+     }
+     memcpy(buf, argv[1], strlen(argv[1]) + 1);
+     return 0;
  }
```
Alternatively, after the length check, `strcpy(buf, argv[1])` is safe, but using `memcpy` with the checked length makes the size relationship explicit.

GLOBAL FIX: Eliminate raw fixed-size global string buffers and unbounded C string APIs from the design. Pass strings around as `{pointer, length}`/bounded views or allocate storage sized from validated input, and centralize copying in a checked helper such as `copy_cstr_checked(dst, dst_size, src)` that returns an error on truncation/overflow. Build with warnings that catch missing prototypes and unsafe patterns (`-Wall -Wextra -Werror`, include proper headers), plus sanitizers/FORTIFY in CI, and ban direct use of `strcpy`/`strcat` in code review or static analysis.
